  {
    question: "Why do Brampton's newer homes have water problems despite modern construction?",
    answer: "Brampton grew from 268,000 to 656,000 people in just 20 years, creating enormous pressure to build fast. Many 2000s-2010s subdivisions in Sandalwood, Gore Meadows, and Castlemore were built with construction shortcuts: builder-grade waterproofing was minimal, drainage stone was thin or wrong type, backfill used clay instead of clear stone, and lot grading was done poorly. The underlying Halton Till clay compresses under building loads, causing settlement cracks. As Tarion warranties expire at 7 years, homeowners discover these defects are now their responsibility."
  },
  {
    question: "How does Etobicoke Creek flooding affect Brampton basements?",
    answer: "Etobicoke Creek and its tributaries are Brampton's primary flood risk. The creek watershed has been heavily developed, reducing natural absorption capacity. During heavy storms and spring melt, the creek exceeds capacity and surrounding water tables rise dramatically. The 2005 and 2013 GTA storm events caused devastating flooding along the creek corridor. Homes within 500 meters of Etobicoke Creek or its tributaries need comprehensive flood protection including exterior waterproofing, backwater valves, high-capacity sump systems with battery backup, and proper lot grading."
