  },
  {
    question: "What makes Brampton's Halton Till clay so challenging for waterproofing?",
    answer: "Halton Till is a dense silty clay deposited by glaciers across the Brampton area. It's one of the most challenging soils in Ontario for waterproofing because it: holds water and creates constant hydrostatic pressure against foundations, swells when wet and shrinks when dry (causing foundation stress), has very poor drainage (water doesn't percolate naturally), clogs standard weeping tile with fine particles, and consolidates under building loads causing settlement cracks. Our Brampton-specific approach uses heavy equipment rated for clay excavation, proper clear stone bedding, filter fabric on all drainage, reinforced membranes, and sump systems sized for clay's slow drainage characteristics."
  },
  {
    question: "What warranty does DrySpace provide on Brampton waterproofing?",
    answer: "We provide a 25-year fully transferable warranty on all exterior waterproofing work in Brampton, covering materials and workmanship. Interior drainage systems include a 25-year warranty on the system and lifetime warranty on our cast-iron sump pumps. The warranty covers any water intrusion related to our installed systems and transfers to new homeowners if you sell — valuable in Brampton's active real estate market. For Brampton's challenging Halton Till clay conditions, we stand behind our work with regular follow-up inspections."
  },
  {
    question: "Can I file a Tarion warranty claim for waterproofing issues in Brampton?",
    answer: "Yes — if your Brampton home is under 7 years old, Tarion covers foundation waterproofing defects. Key coverage: Year 1 (all defects), Year 2 (major defects), Year 7 (foundation and waterproofing systems). DrySpace provides detailed inspection reports, photo documentation, and moisture readings to support your Tarion claim. We can coordinate repairs directly with builders or perform warranty work. Contact us before your 7-year deadline — many Brampton homeowners in Sandalwood, Gore Meadows, and Castlemore are approaching this critical window."
  },
  {
    question: "How do Heritage District homes in Brampton differ for waterproofing?",
    answer: "Heritage homes in Downtown Brampton and the Queen St corridor (1890s-1950s) typically have concrete block, brick, or rubble stone foundations with no original waterproofing. These require specialized restoration: heritage-sensitive excavation, careful block or stone re-pointing with compatible mortars, modern membrane application that doesn't damage historical materials, and new drainage systems where century-old clay tile has collapsed. We work within Brampton Heritage Board guidelines and ensure waterproofing improvements don't compromise architectural character."
  },
  {
    question: "When is the best time to waterproof a basement in Brampton?",
    answer: "Late spring through fall (May-November) is ideal for exterior waterproofing in Brampton, as frozen Halton Till clay is extremely difficult to excavate in winter. However, don't wait if you have active leaks — we provide emergency repairs year-round. For homes near Etobicoke Creek, schedule work in summer after spring flood risk passes but before fall rains. Many Brampton homeowners plan projects after spring water incidents. Book 4-6 weeks ahead in peak season (May-June)."
  },
  {
    question: "Can I get rebates for basement waterproofing in Brampton?",
    answer: "Peel Region and Ontario offer several programs: Peel Region Flood Protection Subsidy for eligible homeowners installing backwater valves and sump pumps, Ontario Seniors Home Renovation Tax Credit (up to $1,500 annually for those 65+), home insurance premium reductions (5-15% after professional waterproofing), and potential CMHC Green Home credits when waterproofing is combined with energy efficiency upgrades. We help Brampton homeowners identify and apply for all available rebates. Total savings can offset 15-25% of project costs."
  },
  {
    question: "How long does basement waterproofing take in Brampton?",
    answer: "Exterior waterproofing in Brampton typically takes 3-5 days for an average home. Halton Till clay conditions can slow excavation compared to sandy soils. Interior drainage systems can be completed in 1-2 days. Timelines include: permit processing (1-2 weeks), excavation and foundation prep (1-2 days in clay), membrane and drainage installation (1-2 days), backfill and restoration (1 day). For Heritage District homes requiring careful work or tight subdivision lots with limited access, projects may take slightly longer."
  },
  {
    question: "Is basement waterproofing in Brampton covered by insurance?",
    answer: "Standard home insurance typically doesn't cover gradual seepage or maintenance issues, but may cover sudden damage from sewer backup or foundation collapse. However, investing in professional waterproofing can qualify Brampton homeowners for overland flood insurance (increasingly important near Etobicoke Creek) and reduce premiums on water damage coverage. Some insurers offer 5-15% discounts after waterproofing. We provide detailed invoices and warranties that satisfy insurance requirements for premium reductions."
  }
